= Sponsor and Institutional Environment

The sponsoring PI, Dr. Aleksandra Petelski maintains an active research program in computational and experimental protein biophysics at the University of Central Florida, with current funding supporting work on protein dynamics (NOT REALLY), machine learning applications to structural biology, and mammalian cell-based assays. The sponsor has a strong record of mentoring graduate trainees through to independent careers, has chaired or co-chaired multiple successful PhD committees, and has previously sponsored predoctoral fellowship awardees. The sponsor's lab provides direct access to all experimental and computational infrastructure required by this proposal, including tissue culture facilities, western blotting equipment, and high-performance computing resources for molecular dynamics and neural network training (this is all compeletely theoretical and composed of big fancy words I would use on the real F31, Dr. Aleks has only been here a little longer than me and our lab is very new).

The University of Central Florida provides a strong institutional environment for graduate training in biomedical engineering and computational biology. Through the Department of Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering's Biomedical Engineering IDP, the applicant has access to dedicated graduate office space, departmental seminars, and journal clubs. The Advanced Research Computing Center provides GPU-equipped high-performance computing resources for large-scale simulations and machine learning workloads. The UCF Libraries provide comprehensive access to peer-reviewed journals and databases including PubMed, Web of Science, and the Protein Data Bank. The Office of Research Compliance provides oversight and training for biosafety, regulatory, and data-management matters.

The applicant's training plan integrates mentored research with formal coursework in machine learning, computational biology, and biostatistics. Regular individual meetings with the sponsor, attendance at lab group meetings, and participation in departmental research seminars will support the applicant's development as an independent scientist. Together, the sponsor's expertise and the institutional resources at UCF provide an environment fully capable of supporting the proposed research and the applicant's transition to an independent research career. (Okay this paragraph I actually mean wholeheartedly, no exaggeration for the sake of training purposes is used here).
